KMSubtraction: Imputation of unreported subgroup survival data utilizing reconstructed data from published Kaplan-Meier survival curves

Joseph J Zhao

In this guide, we demonstrate KMSubtraction, an approach to retrieve unreported subgroup survival data from published Kaplan-Meier survival curves (KMSubtractionMatch). We also discuss methods to evaluate the accuracy of this process (KMSubtractionEvaluateMatch).

Start by loading the following functions and packages. We will use the colon dataset from the survival package in R.

library(devtools)
install_github("josephjzhao/KMSubtraction")
library(KMSubtraction)
data(cancer, package="survival")

Create curves for the scenario

For this example, we will be using the colon dataset from the survival package. We will assume the scenario in which, Kaplan-Meier (KM) curves of treatment outcomes with systemic therapy (5FU+Lev vs Lev) is only presented for patients in the overall cohort and patients with more than 4 positive lymph nodes (the subgroup).

As such, KM curves for patients with less than 4 positive lymph nodes is unavailable.

If you already have reconstructed curves, please skip to the implementation of KMSubtractionMatch below.

df_overall=subset(colon, !colon$rx=="Obs" & colon$etype==2)
df_subgroup=subset(colon, colon$node4==1 & !colon$rx=="Obs" & colon$etype==2)

km_overall=survfit(Surv(time, status) ~ rx, data=df_overall)
km_subgroup=survfit(Surv(time, status) ~ rx, data=df_subgroup)

# create maximum xy coordinates for rescaling later
fu_max=4000
y_max=1

# curves, as shown in this hypothetical publication
ggsurvplot(km_overall,                    
          data = df_overall,  
          size=0.5,
          risk.table = TRUE,    
          censor.shape="|",
          censor.size = 1.2,
          conf.int = T, 
          xlim = c(0,max(df_overall$time)),
          xlab = "Time, days",  
          break.time.by = 500, 
          ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
          risk.table.fontsize=3,
          tables.theme = theme_cleantable(),
          title="Overall")

ggsurvplot(km_subgroup,                    
          data = df_subgroup,  
          size=0.5,
          risk.table = TRUE,    
          censor.shape="|",
          censor.size = 1.2,
          conf.int = T, 
          xlim = c(0,max(df_subgroup$time)),
          xlab = "Time, days",  
          break.time.by = 500, 
          ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
          risk.table.fontsize=3,
          tables.theme = theme_cleantable(),
          title="Subgroup (>4 positive lymph nodes)")

Print curves for the scenario

Create the curves for each arm.

km_overall_levfu=survfit(Surv(time, status) ~ 1, data=subset(df_overall, df_overall$rx=="Lev+5FU"))
km_overall_lev=survfit(Surv(time, status) ~ 1, data=subset(df_overall, df_overall$rx=="Lev"))
km_subgroup_levfu=survfit(Surv(time, status) ~ 1, data=subset(df_subgroup, df_subgroup$rx=="Lev+5FU"))
km_subgroup_lev=survfit(Surv(time, status) ~ 1, data=subset(df_subgroup, df_subgroup$rx=="Lev"))

Export the KM curves. For simplicity, we will print each curve individually.

png(paste0("km_overall_levfu_curve.png"), width=500, height=500, units="px")
plot(km_overall_levfu, col=c("red3"), conf.int = F, lwd=0.3, xlim=c(0,fu_max), main="Overall (Lev+5FU)")
points(matrix(c(0,fu_max,0,fu_max,0,0,y_max,y_max), ncol=2, nrow=4), col="red2", pch=16, cex=0.1)
dev.off()

png(paste0("km_overall_lev_curve.png"), width=500, height=500, units="px")
plot(km_overall_lev, col=c("red3"), conf.int = F, lwd=0.3, xlim=c(0,fu_max), main="Overall (Lev)")
points(matrix(c(0,fu_max,0,fu_max,0,0,y_max,y_max), ncol=2, nrow=4), col="red2", pch=16, cex=0.1)
dev.off()

png(paste0("km_subgroup_levfu_curve.png"), width=500, height=500, units="px")
plot(km_subgroup_levfu, col=c("red3"), conf.int = F, lwd=0.3, xlim=c(0,fu_max), main="Subgroup (patients with >4 postitive lymph nodes) (Lev+5FU)")
points(matrix(c(0,fu_max,0,fu_max,0,0,y_max,y_max), ncol=2, nrow=4), col="red2", pch=16, cex=0.1)

png(paste0("km_subgroup_lev_curve.png"), width=500, height=500, units="px")
plot(km_subgroup_lev, col=c("red3"), conf.int = F, lwd=0.3, xlim=c(0,fu_max), main="Subgroup (patients with >4 postitive lymph nodes) (Lev)")
points(matrix(c(0,fu_max,0,fu_max,0,0,y_max,y_max), ncol=2, nrow=4), col="red2", pch=16, cex=0.1)
dev.off()

Identify curve points on png file

Reconstruct the dataset by identifying the points of each curve on the png KM curves. We will use the SelectDataPoints function as created above. Do note that this only applies if the color for each curve is the same as above.

Alternatively, you may choose to manually do so using the digitize package. https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/digitize/digitize.pdf Or the built in function getpoints() in IPDfromKM package. https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/IPDfromKM/IPDfromKM.pdf

im_overall_levfu=image_read("km_overall_levfu_curve.png")
im_overall_lev=image_read("km_overall_lev_curve.png")
im_subgroup_levfu=image_read("km_subgroup_levfu_curve.png")
im_subgroup_lev=image_read("km_subgroup_lev_curve.png")

df_clicks_levfu_overall=SelectDataPoints(im_overall_levfu, fu_max) 
df_clicks_lev_overall=SelectDataPoints(im_overall_lev, fu_max) 
df_clicks_levfu_subgroup=SelectDataPoints(im_subgroup_levfu, fu_max) 
df_clicks_lev_subgroup=SelectDataPoints(im_subgroup_lev, fu_max)

IPDfromKM

Using the IPDfromKM package, we will reconstruct each curve.

df_recon_levfu_overall=getIPD(prep=preprocess(dat=df_clicks_levfu_overall[,1:2], 
                               trisk=survminer::ggsurvtable(km_overall_levfu, data=km_overall, break.time.by = 500)$risk.table$data$time, 
                               nrisk=survminer::ggsurvtable(km_overall_levfu, data=km_overall, break.time.by = 500)$risk.table$data$n.risk, 
                               maxy=1),
                                armID=1, tot.events=NULL)$IPD

df_recon_lev_overall=getIPD(prep=preprocess(dat=df_clicks_lev_overall[,1:2], 
                               trisk=survminer::ggsurvtable(km_overall_lev, data=km_overall, break.time.by = 500)$risk.table$data$time, 
                               nrisk=survminer::ggsurvtable(km_overall_lev, data=km_overall, break.time.by = 500)$risk.table$data$n.risk, 
                               maxy=1),
                                armID=1, tot.events=NULL)$IPD

df_recon_levfu_subgroup=getIPD(prep=preprocess(dat=df_clicks_levfu_subgroup[,1:2], 
                               trisk=survminer::ggsurvtable(km_subgroup_levfu, data=km_subgroup, break.time.by = 500)$risk.table$data$time, 
                               nrisk=survminer::ggsurvtable(km_subgroup_levfu, data=km_subgroup, break.time.by = 500)$risk.table$data$n.risk, 
                               maxy=1),
                                armID=1, tot.events=NULL)$IPD

df_recon_lev_subgroup=getIPD(prep=preprocess(dat=df_clicks_lev_subgroup[,1:2], 
                               trisk=survminer::ggsurvtable(km_subgroup_lev, data=km_subgroup, break.time.by = 500)$risk.table$data$time, 
                               nrisk=survminer::ggsurvtable(km_subgroup_lev, data=km_subgroup, break.time.by = 500)$risk.table$data$n.risk, 
                               maxy=1),
                                armID=1, tot.events=NULL)$IPD

KMSubtractionMatch

Conduct minimum cost bipartite matching through the Hungarian algorithm with the RcppHungarian package in R. Patients with events and censorships will be matched separately. We will use the predefined function KMSubtractionMatch as created above. More information regarding the Hungarian algorithm may be found here https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/RcppHungarian/vignettes/Introduction-to-RcppHungarian.html.

df_match_levfu=KMSubtractionMatch_BP(df_recon_levfu_overall, df_recon_levfu_subgroup)
df_match_lev=KMSubtractionMatch_BP(df_recon_lev_overall, df_recon_lev_subgroup)

KMSubtractionEvaluateMatch

We may now evaluate the quality of matching by comparing patients in the cohort with >4 positive lymph nodes, and the matched patients from the overall cohort. We will use the KMSubtractionEvaluateMatch function as created above. We will do so by inspecting Empirical cumulative distribution functions and the KolmogorovSmirnov Test of follow-up times between matched pairs as well as with Bland-Altman plots to explore discrepancies between matched pairs.

KMSubtractionEvaluateMatch(df_match_levfu)

KMSubtractionEvaluateMatch(df_match_lev)

Finally, we may retrieve the unmatched patients, which may be assumed to be from the unreported cohort - patients with less than 4 positive lymph nodes. And we may compare it to the actual patients from the colon dataset.

df_imputed=rbind(cbind(subset(df_match_levfu, is.na(df_match_levfu$matchid)), rx="Lev+5FU"),
            cbind(subset(df_match_lev, is.na(df_match_lev$matchid)), rx="Lev"))

km_imputed=survfit(Surv(time, status) ~ rx, data=df_imputed)
km_original=survfit(Surv(time, status) ~ rx, data=subset(colon, !colon$rx=="Obs" & colon$node4==0 & colon$etype==2))

# comparing KM curves
ggsurvplot(km_imputed,                    
          data = df_imputed,  
          size=0.5,
          risk.table = TRUE,    
          censor.shape="|",
          censor.size = 1.2,
          conf.int = T, 
          xlim = c(0,max(df_imputed$time)),
          xlab = "Time, days",  
          break.time.by = 500, 
          ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
          risk.table.fontsize=3,
          tables.theme = theme_cleantable(),
          title="Imputed with KMSubtraction (<=4 positive lymph nodes)")

ggsurvplot(km_original,                    
          data = subset(colon, !colon$rx=="Obs" & colon$node4==0 & colon$etype==2),  
          size=0.5,
          risk.table = TRUE,    
          censor.shape="|",
          censor.size = 1.2,
          conf.int = T, 
          xlim = c(0,max(subset(colon, !colon$rx=="Obs"  & colon$etype==2& colon$node4==0)$time)),
          xlab = "Time, days",  
          break.time.by = 500, 
          ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
          risk.table.fontsize=3,
          tables.theme = theme_cleantable(),
          title="Original (<=4 positive lymph nodes)")

# We may also examine the comparative distribution of follow-up times between the imputed and original cohort on Empirical cumulative distribution functions and with the KolmogorovSmirnov Test

ks.test_lev=ks.test(subset(df_imputed, df_imputed$rx=="Lev")$time, 
                subset(colon, !colon$rx=="Obs" & colon$node4==0 & colon$rx=="Lev" & colon$etype==2)$time)
                          
df_cum_lev=bind_rows(cbind(subset(df_imputed, df_imputed$rx=="Lev"),strata="Imputed"), 
                cbind(subset(colon, !colon$rx=="Obs" & colon$node4==0 & colon$rx=="Lev" & colon$etype==2),strata="Original"))

ggplot(df_cum_lev, aes(time, colour = strata)) +
          stat_ecdf()+
          theme_minimal()+
          scale_colour_manual(values=c("#000000", "#00b3aa"))+
          labs(title="Empirical cumulative distribution function (Lev)" , x="Follow-up (days)")+
          annotate("text", y=0.7, x=1,  hjust = 0,label = paste("Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test, p=", format(round(ks.test_lev$p.value,3), nsmall=3), sep=''), size = 3)

ks.test_levfu=ks.test(subset(df_imputed, df_imputed$rx=="Lev+5FU")$time, 
                    subset(colon, !colon$rx=="Obs" & colon$node4==0 & colon$rx=="Lev+5FU" & colon$etype==2)$time)
                          
df_cum_levfu=bind_rows(cbind(subset(df_imputed, df_imputed$rx=="Lev+5FU"),strata="Imputed"), 
                    cbind(subset(colon, !colon$rx=="Obs" & colon$node4==0 & colon$rx=="Lev+5FU" & colon$etype==2),strata="Original"))

ggplot(df_cum_levfu, aes(time, colour = strata)) +
          stat_ecdf()+
          theme_minimal()+
          scale_colour_manual(values=c("#000000", "#00b3aa"))+
          labs(title="Empirical cumulative distribution function (Lev+5FU)" , x="Follow-up (days)")+
          annotate("text", y=0.7, x=1,  hjust = 0,label = paste("Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test, p=", format(round(ks.test_levfu$p.value,3), nsmall=3), sep=''), size = 3)

# similar HRs demonstrated on marginal Cox proportional hazard models
colon$rx=colon$rx %>% as.character
coxph(Surv(time, status) ~ rx, data=subset(colon, !colon$rx=="Obs" & colon$node4==0 & colon$etype==2))
